07/20/2021,748.363(8) - Reports and Record Keeping,Reports and Record Keeping,No,08/03/2021,08/03/2021,D:Reports and Record Keeping,Medium,No,"During the monitoring inspection, four staff files were reviewed. One staff file did not contain a signed and dated statement in where an employee must immediately report any suspected incident of child abuse, neglect, or exploitation to the Texas Abuse and Neglect Hot line and to the operation s administrator and/or administrator s. 748.831(b): The same staff file did not contain orientation documentation.  ","748.363(8) Personnel records - Include signed dated statement by the employee that he must immediately report suspected child abuse, neglect, or exploitation.
The Human Resources Director has developed an attestation that reads:
I understand that I must immediately report any suspected incident of child abuse, neglect or exploitation to the Texas Abuse and Neglect Hotline and to TNCs administrator or administrators designee (CNS).
New hires that work with the Child/Adolescent programs are now required to read and sign the attestation.  Current employees were provided the statement with the expectation that they sign and return the statement immediately.  This will be tracked electronically and monitored through Healthstream. Non-compliance of completion is reported to the appropriate supervisor, Manager, CEO, COO, DON, Director of Clinical Services and the Compliance Officer/PI Director.  All current employees were provided the new statement to sign and return to Human Resources. 
Each new employee has an orientation checklist that is specific to their job description.  The supervisor of each employee is responsible for assuring that the orientation checklist is completed.  The completed checklist is forwarded to the Human Resources department who will monitor for completion.  Instances of noncompliance will be reported to the appropriate supervisor, Manager, CEO, COO, DON, Director of Clinical Services and the  Compliance Officer/PI Director.   "
07/20/2021,748.931(a)(1)(B)(i) - Training and Professional ,Training and Professional Development,No,08/03/2021,08/03/2021,F:Training and Professional Development,Medium High,Yes,"During the monitoring inspection, four staff files were reviewed. It was noted that four of the four staff files did not provide documentation regarding Normalcy training. 748.749(b)(5): One of the four staff files reviewed had training certificated that did not specify the training hours. ","748.931(a)(1)(B)(i) Annual Training-Must include 2 hours on trauma informed care
The Human Resources Trainer assigned all Ponderosa (Child and Adolescent Units) staff the courses available on the Texas HHSC website that relate to trauma informed care and normalcy.  This action was implemented immediately.  These two courses are assigned annually.  The Human Resources department tracks the completion of courses and notifies supervisors if employees do not complete required training.  The assignments were effective August 1, 2021.  Non-compliance of training is reported to the appropriate supervisor, the appropriate manager, CEO,COO, DON, Director of Clinical Services and Compliance Officer/PI Director.  
The Human Resources Department will add hours of training to all training provided at the facility.  The Director or designee will audit files on an ongoing basis for compliance.  Omissions will be corrected immediately by the Human Resources trainer who will add the hours of training to documentation."
07/20/2021,748.3441(a) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,08/03/2021,08/03/2021,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium High,Yes,"During a walk through of the operation, 9 large cans, an unopened box of ravioles and a plastic jar of liquid were observed to be expired in the Cafeteria's pantry area. ","748.3441(a): Food Preparation-Food & drinks must be of safe quality, stored, prepared, distributed, & served under sanitary & safe conditions.
The Food Service Manager labeled the shelves in the dry storage area (picture attached).  The Food Service Manager clarified that the top shelf is for emergency food items like tuna, ravioli, peanut butter and long shelf life foods. The lower shelf is for dented cans, damaged items and items that arrived with a limited time before expiration. These food products remain on this shelf until the food delivery representative comes and gives credit to the account.
The Food Service Manager will monitor the dry storage area weekly to assure that the labels stay in place."
06/28/2021,748.3441(a) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,07/12/2021,07/12/2021,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium High,No,"During a follow up inspection, one frozen food item and several refridgerated condensed dairy cartons were observed to be expired in the Cafeteria and the same condensed dairy cartons observed also had mold on the outside of the lid area and were not of good quality.","The operation reported the expired food items found during the site survey were discarded immediately. The Food Service Manager was notified of the expired items found. The Food Service Manager and the senior Food Service worker have re-educated all Food Service staff as of 7/6/2021 regarding the practices listed below that are to be followed on a daily basis. The education was presented individually to each Food Service worker.

	Food items are rotated with a first in, first out practice.
	When new food items are stocked, the current food items are checked for expiration.
	All food items retrieved for use are checked before use. They are checked for expiration dates, appearance and odor.
	If a food item does not have a date, it is to be thrown out.
	Cooked food that is stored is thrown out within 6 days of being cooked.
	Daily cleaning and food check of the walk-ins are completed.

The operation also reported that the Lead Cook for the day is responsible for execution of a daily cleaning checklist which includes checking for expired or compromised food. The Food Service Manager provides oversight monitoring to assure the above practices are followed consistently.  "
04/19/2021,748.3441(a) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,06/16/2021,06/28/2021,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium High,Yes,"Two children in care reported that they were served spoiled/rotten milk and that this may have been due to staff leaving the milk out of the refrigerator after use for a period of time as the milk had not been expired yet, but that it was spoiled and bad/rotten tasting. Two children in care also reported the food was not good. Staff leaving foods that should be refrigerated out for a period of time can be dangerous and may cause food-borne illnesses.","Licensing conducted an unannounced visit to the operation and did a walk-through of the Cafeteria and Chaparral unit. Licensing checked 4 out of 4 refrigerators and 2 out of 2 freezers in the kitchen area and 2 refrigerators in the dining area of the Cafeteria near the kitchen. There were no spoiled whole milk, 1% or 2% milk, and/or soy almond milk observed. The refrigerators where the milk was stored were at proper temperatures of 40 degrees or less. Licensing also checked the refrigerator in the break room of the Chaparral unit, the almond milk and other milk was observed to not be expired, did not have a bad odor, were of normal consistency, and of good quality.

On 6/16/21, the operation also provided through email, the following compliance response:

The Director of Nursing provided re-education to nursing staff on 6/16/21 relating to safe parameters for food to be left unrefrigerated.  On 6/15/21, the Director of Nursing posted signs in the kitchen/nutrition areas with educational information related to food storage. The information includes the bacterial growth rate in milk related to temperature (obtained from USDA food safety fact sheet) and a reminder to discard any refrigerated food items after 30 minutes at room temperature.

Refrigerator temperatures are monitored and documented daily. Any out of range temperatures result in immediate action to correct the temperature. Daily checklists include inspection of refrigerator for temperatures and expired food/drinks. Expired items are discarded immediately. The checklists are forwarded to the Director of Nursing for review.

Although there were no concerns regarding the above mentioned milk products, during the walk-through, other food/drink items were observed to be expired, and/or unsealed, and/or to have mold. It was addressed with the operation that these items should be discarded and open food items should be sealed. Please refer to the follow up inspection for today's visit for further information."
